{
  "doc_id": "27882",
  "text": "Spinal cord injury (SCI) is a major cause for chronic disability that profoundly affects patients' autonomy and quality of life. Despite the abundance of empirical evidence on the local effects of SCI along the spinal cord, our understanding of the concomitant changes in brain anatomy and function is still limited. Animal models of SCI showed controversial results ranging from extensive neuronal cell death in cortical areas [CITATION_1] and the rubrospinal tract [CITATION_2] to lack of upper motoneuron degeneration or cell death of corticospinal neurons [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The lack of in-depth knowledge about the impact of SCI on brain anatomy in humans highlights the need to provide in vivo analytic proof of concomitant structural changes that could inform clinical decision making in respect to treatment and prognosis.",
